<TITLE> Chad's oil output not affected by violence:minister </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 N'DJAMENA, Feb 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Chad's 140,000-160,000 barrels per day (bpd) oil output was not affected by a rebel attack on the capital a week ago, but the violence disrupted prospecting and plans for a new refinery, the oil minister said on Monday. "Production has continued as normal," Oil Minister Emmanuel Nadingar told Reuters amid burnt papers and broken furniture at his ministry building which was looted following the Feb. 2-3 assault on the capital N'Djamena by eastern rebels. Prospecting in the Bongor Basin southeast of N'Djamena has been disrupted since expatriate workers fled the two days of heavy fighting in the city, Nadingar said. "Most of their personnel are based here in N'Djamena ... they were evacuated," he said. Dozens of Chinese expatriate oil workers have been living at a game lodge in Waza National Park across the border in neighbouring Cameroon since the violence. Prospecting operations by Taiwan's OPIC have continued near Chad's only existing production facilities in the Doba field in the south of the country, which was unaffected by the week-long rebel advance across the country, Nadingar said. However, plans to start work on a new 60,000 bpd refinery within the next month or two were likely to be delayed, Nadingar said. "There are contracts to finalise. That will slip a bi
